{
  "texts": [
    "The research suggests that offloading pervades many cognitive task domains, including problem-solving, memory, planning and verbal communication.",
    "For example, participants in experiments have been shown to rely on the physical structure of a problem space as a kind of 'external memory' across a wide range of conditions, including when refraining from this strategy doesn't come at a performance cost (Gilbert, 2015; Risko & Dunn, 2015).",
    "Hand gestures during speech occur even when interlocutors cannot see them and seem to have a role in helping speakers formulate and structure what they are saying (Hostetter & Alibali 2008).",
    "Other, so-called 'epistemic actions' (Kirsh & Maglio, 1994) involve reorientations of an agent's body or environment that are 'pragmatically' unnecessary (i.e.",
    "they do not directly tend towards the agent's goal), but which improve performance by making necessary information more readily available."
  ]
}